{# FAQ #}
<section class="py-12">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <h2 class="section-heading mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="card p-5 group" open>
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Is Spain a good destination for tech careers?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Absolutely. Barcelona is one of Europe's fastest-growing tech hubs, hosting companies like Glovo, Typeform, and Travelperk, along with offices of major multinationals. Madrid's tech scene is also booming. Spain attracted record venture capital in recent years, and the government actively supports tech growth with favorable visa policies.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Do I need to speak Spanish to work in tech in Spain?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Many international tech companies in Barcelona and Madrid operate primarily in English. However, learning Spanish significantly improves your daily life and integration. In smaller cities or more traditional companies, Spanish is more important. Catalan is also widely spoken in Barcelona but rarely required at work.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What visa options are available for tech workers in Spain?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Spain offers several pathways: the <strong>Highly Qualified Professional visa</strong> for employed tech workers, the <strong>EU Blue Card</strong>, and the <strong>Digital Nomad visa</strong> for remote workers. Companies that sponsor visas handle most of the paperwork. Processing typically takes 4–8 weeks with employer support.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          How does the cost of living compare to other European tech hubs?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Spain is significantly more affordable than London, Amsterdam, or Munich. Barcelona rent averages €1,100–€1,600/month for a one-bedroom, while Madrid is slightly cheaper. Cities like Valencia and Malaga offer even lower costs. While salaries are lower than Northern Europe, the purchasing power and quality of life often balance out. Use our <a href="/tools/cost-of-living/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Cost of Living Calculator</a> for comparisons.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

